      <body>
         <div type="edition">
            <ab>
               <lb n="1"/>
               <expan><abbr>D</abbr><ex>is</ex></expan>
               <expan><abbr>M</abbr><ex>anibus</ex></expan>.
                <lb n="2"/>
               <persName>
                  <name type="gentilicium" key="Appalia">Appaliae</name>
                  <name type="cognomen" key="Felicitas">Felici
                <lb break="no" n="3"/>tati</name>
               </persName> filiae dul
                <lb break="no" n="4"/>cissimae bene
                <lb n="5"/>merenti, <persName>
                  <name type="gentilicium" key="Appalius">Appa
                <lb break="no" n="6"/>lius</name>
                  <name type="cognomen" key="Felicissimus">Felicissi
                <lb break="no" n="7"/>mus</name>
               </persName>
               <persName>
                  <name type="gentilicium" key="Appalia">Appalia</name>
                  <lb n="8"/>
                  <name type="cognomen" key="Nice">Nice</name>
               </persName> fecerun
                <lb break="no" n="9"/>t, quae vixit
                <lb n="10"/>
               <expan><abbr>an</abbr><ex>nis</ex></expan>
               <num value="6">VI</num>, <expan><abbr>di</abbr><ex>ebus</ex></expan>
               <num value="40">XXXX</num>.
            </ab>
            <!-- The marked up transcription goes here, surrounded by <ab> </ab> elements -->
         </div>
         <div type="translation">
            <p>To the Divine Spirits. For Appalia Felicitas, dearest daughter,
                    well-deserving. Appalius Felicissimus (and) Appalia Nice made (this for her),
                    who lived for six years (and) forty days.</p>
         </div>
         <div type="commentary">
            <p>This inscription is a plaster copy of <hi rend="italic">AE</hi> (1974): 190.
                    The original was found in Latium, so this inscription was probably also
                    manufactured there. </p>
         </div>
